AN ACT relating to guardianship; making various changes relating
to guardianship; and providing other matters properly
relating thereto.
Legislative Counsel’s Digest:
1 Existing law establishes the Supported Decision-Making Act, which authorizes
2 an adult with a disability to enter into a supported decision-making agreement at
3 any time if the adult enters into the agreement voluntarily and understands the
4 nature and effect of the agreement. (Chapter 162C of NRS) Section 1 of this bill
5 defines the term “supported decision-making agreement” for the purposes of the
6 provisions of law governing guardianship of adults.
7 Existing law defines the term “incapacitated” for the purposes of the provisions
8 of law governing guardianships of adults. (NRS 159.019) Section 3 of this bill
9 expands the definition to include a person who is unable to understand the nature
10 and effect of a supported decision-making agreement.
11 Existing law: (1) authorizes a proposed protected person, a governmental
12 agency, a nonprofit organization or an interested person to petition the court for the
13 appointment of a guardian; (2) requires such a petition to include certain
14 information; and (3) requires that the petitioner provide the court with an
15 assessment of the needs of the proposed protected person, which must be completed
16 by a licensed physician. (NRS 159.044) Section 4 of this bill requires a petition for
17 the appointment of a guardian to contain an attestation that information on
18 supported decision-making agreements has been provided to the proposed protected
19 person. Section 4 also requires that a licensed physician completing such an
20 assessment include a determination of whether the proposed protected person is
21 unable to understand the nature and effect of a supported decision-making
22 agreement. Section 4 provides that if the licensed physician determines that a
23 proposed protected person is able to understand the nature and effect of a supported
24 decision-making agreement, the petitioner is required to prove to the satisfaction of
-
