– 2 –
25 the court that a supported decision-making agreement is not a reasonable alternative
26 to the guardianship.
27 Existing law requires a guardian of the person to make a written report
28 containing certain information, file the report with the court and serve the report on
29 the protected person and any attorney for the protected person. (NRS 159.081)
30 Section 5 of this bill requires that such a report include: (1) a description of certain
31 skills and abilities of the protected person; and (2) an explanation as to why a
32 supported decision-making agreement is not a reasonable alternative to the
33 guardianship.
34 Existing law authorizes a protected person, the guardian or another person to
35 petition the court for the termination or modification of a guardianship. Existing
36 law provides that for such a petition to be granted, the petitioner must prove that the
37 termination or modification of the guardianship is in the best interests of the
38 protected person. (NRS 159.1905) Section 6 of this bill provides that such a
39 petition may also be granted if the petitioner shows that the protected person has
40 entered into a supported decision-making agreement in lieu of the guardianship.
41 Existing law establishes the Protected Persons’ Bill of Rights, which sets forth
42 certain specific rights of each protected person. (NRS 159.327, 159.328) Section 7
43 of this bill provides that a protected person has the right to be educated about
44 alternatives to a guardianship, including, without limitation, a supported decision-
45 making agreement.
